abstract: >-
  A personal essay collection and structured knowledge graph mapping the three
  major Buddhist Abhidharma traditions (Theravāda, Sarvāstivāda, Yogācāra) onto
  contemporary frameworks in computational phenomenology — predictive processing,
  active inference, Global Workspace Theory, Parallel Distributed Processing, and
  related approaches. Comprises fourteen essays (seven themes × English + Japanese), a
  cross-tradition dharma comparison table (~130 dharmas across nine sheets), and
  a JSON-LD knowledge graph (~284 nodes, schema.org + custom vocabulary) with
  bilingual labels and Sanskrit / Pāli / Chinese philological alignment. An
  interactive 2D/3D viewer is provided. v0.3.0 adds Theme 7 (Cessation and
  continuity without a self) — meditative cessation (nirodha samāpatti) as the
  sharpest form of the no-self continuity problem, set against four Abhidharma
  answers to what carries continuity across the gap (Sarvāstivāda prāpti /
  Sautrāntika bīja / Yogācāra ālaya-vijñāna / Theravāda bhavaṅga) and
  Laukkonen et al. 2023's active-inference model of cessation. It also relicenses
  the repository to CC0 1.0 and federates the line into the shimo4228
  research-program hub. Developed in collaboration with the Claude
  language model (Anthropic) for synthesis, cross-tradition mapping, and graph
  encoding; the author retains responsibility for all claims.
